applications.name: Magnetic Material
applications.justification: Electron donor (D)/electron acceptor (A) charge transfer (CT) systems are potentially good magnetic materials. This is because such a system has two properties that are very useful in producing high-efficiency magnetic materials: (1) its spin state switches between two critical states, neutral (N) and ionic (I), involving electron transfer (ET), and (2) the ionic state, with a newly produced spin set, often allows a relatively strong spin correlation |J|, sometimes of over 100 K, supported by CT between ionized D+ and A– units.

experimental_properties.summary: The emission peaks of compounds 1–4 are observed at 558nm (λ ex =284nm), 547nm (λ ex =265nm), 412nm (λ ex =340nm) and 429nm (λ ex =325nm), respectively.

synthesis.justification: The preparation of 3 was similar to that of 1 except that 4,4′-tmbpt (0.03g, 0.1mmol) was used instead of 3,4′-tmbpt. Colorless crystals of 3 were collected in a 37% yield.
synthesis.procedure: Mix AgNO3 (0.051g, 0.3mmol), 4,4′-tmbpt (0.03g, 0.1mmol), Hbtc (0.021g, 0.1mmol), NaOH (0.012g, 0.3mmol) and 8mL H2O. Place the mixture in a 15mL Teflon reactor. Heat the reactor at 130°C for 3 days. Cool the mixture to room temperature at a rate of 10°C/h. Collect colorless crystals of the compound in a 37% yield.
